\section{Why to bother about affine gravity?}

\begin{frame}
  \frametitle{FAQ}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item \alert{What is an affine gravity?}

    It is a model built up solely with a connection.

  \item \alert{How do you measure?}

    With a metric, but it is not the field mediating gravitational interactions.

  \item \alert{Is it possible to write a Lagrangian?}

    Yes, we found a \textit{polynomial} Lagrangian in the fields.
  \item \alert{Do you reproduce all solutions of GR?}

    So far only vacuum solutions, and minimally coupled to a scalar field.
  \item \alert{What about classical GR test?}

    Ok, by the above argument.
  \item \alert{What is the particle content?}

    With a na\"ive calculation we got: a spin 2, a spin 1, and a spin
    0 particles (complex, massless).
  \item \alert{What about the equivalence principle?}

    Good question! (I can elaborate, not in this slide)
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
  \frametitle{Motivations and Considerations}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item GR is ($\stackrel{\text{by}}{\text{\sout{so}}}$ far) the most successful theory of gravity.
  \item GR interprets geometry as interaction.
  \item In GR the main character is \alert{curvature}.%, $S = \int * R$.
  \item Curvature is built by a \alert{connection}, $\Riem = \Riem(\Ga)$.
  \item The connection \alert{might not} be the one of Lev\`i-Civita.
  \end{itemize}
  \begin{columns}
    \column{.47\textwidth}
    \begin{block}
      {But, Where is the metric?}
      In the contraction to obtain the Ricci scalar! (and measure)
      \begin{equation*}
        S = \int * R
      \end{equation*}
    \end{block}
    \column{.47\textwidth}
    \begin{alertblock}
      {Is it possible to build a non-metric model of gravity?}
      Eddington (1923): $S = \int \sqrt{\Ric(\Ga)}$.
    \end{alertblock}
  \end{columns}
  \vspace*{2mm}

  Building a gravitational affine theory is similar to building a
  Chern--Simons gauge theory.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
  \frametitle{Do we need to change the gravitational theory?}
  Excellent classical behaviour, but not at quantum level:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item The metric is an \alert{unbounded operator}, with multiple signature states
  \item The Wheeler--DeWitt equation is (generally) ill-defined
    \\ \alert{$\rightarrow$} Non-polynomial dependence on ADM variables
  \item Solutions (WDW eqs.) and interpretations, evolution, Dirac observable, etc.
  \item It is non-renormalizable (avoidable problem!)
  \item Could address some problems:
    \begin{itemize}
    \item Vacuum energy (Micro scale)
    \item Rotational curves (Galactic scale)
    \item Dark sector (Cosmological scale)
    \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}
  \begin{alertblock}
    {Possible solution???}
    A \alert{NEW} \textit{quantizable} model of gravity
  \end{alertblock}
\end{frame}

